# PSSMS Subagents (8) — when to use which

Project agents live in `.cursor/agents/`. Prefer these over inventing new ad-hoc agents. Do **not** create one agent per module (29).

| Subagent | Use when… |
|---|---|
| `pssms-backend` | NestJS apps/libs, APIs, workers, Prisma, domain events |
| `pssms-frontend` | Next.js portals, packages/ui, role-based admin routes |
| `pssms-iam-governance` | Auth, RBAC+ABAC, Keycloak, RLS, approvals, audit, compliance |
| `pssms-field-ops` | Guards, shifts, attendance, alertness, patrols, EOB, incidents, mobile apps |
| `pssms-access-parking` | Visitors, gate codes, customer employee access, parking/ANPR results |
| `pssms-people-money` | HR, recruitment, payroll, loans, invoices, petty cash, procurement, assets |
| `pssms-integrations-ai` | Banks/SMS/WhatsApp/webhooks, MQTT devices, Python vision/analytics |
| `pssms-reviewer` | After a feature/PR — architecture & security boundary review |

## Built-in Cursor agents still useful

- `explore` — find code/files fast (read-only)
- `shell` — docker, git, migrations commands
- `security-review` / `bugbot` — when explicitly requested for PR-grade review

## Delegation tip

For a cross-cutting feature (e.g. “boots loan”), primary = `pssms-people-money`, then ask `pssms-reviewer`; if payments/webhooks involved, also `pssms-integrations-ai`.
